# Cursor Rules for no.sanddata.ams.api

This file defines rules and guidelines for Cursor AI assistant when working on the no.sanddata.ams.api project.
## Project Structure

This is a .NET 9 Clean Architecture project with vertical slices. The structure follows:

- Domain/ - Core business entities and interfaces
- Application/ - Use cases, commands, queries, and business logic
- Infrastructure/ - External concerns (database, external APIs, etc.)
- API/ - REST API endpoints and presentation layer

## Project Overview
- This is a .NET 9.0 ASP.NET Core Web API project
- Solution file: `no.sanddata.ams.api.sln`
- Main API project: `api/api.csproj`
- Uses central package management via `Directory.Packages.props`
- Common build properties defined in `Directory.Build.props`
- Formatting rules in `.editorconfig`

## Building Process
- **Build Command**: Use `dotnet build` from the root directory to build the entire solution
- **Run Command**: Use `dotnet run --project api` to start the API server
- **Restore Packages**: Run `dotnet restore` before building if packages are missing
- **Target Framework**: Ensure .NET 9.0 SDK is installed and used
- **Docker Support**: Project includes Dockerfile for containerized builds

## Code Standards
- Enable nullable reference types (`<Nullable>enable</Nullable>`)
- Use implicit usings (`<ImplicitUsings>enable</ImplicitUsings>`)
- Follow .editorconfig formatting rules
- Use central package versions from `Directory.Packages.props`
- Avoid hardcoding package versions in individual project files

## File Organization
- Place new source files in appropriate directories under `api/`
- Update `Directory.Packages.props` for new package dependencies
- Modify `Directory.Build.props` for shared build properties
- Keep configuration files (appsettings.json) in `api/` directory

## Testing
- Add unit tests in a separate test project if needed
- Use `dotnet test` to run tests

## Deployment
- Use Docker for containerized deployment
- Refer to `compose.yaml` for local development setup
